<section><title> Second-Order LHCC Equations </title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Second-order linear homogeneous constant coefficient (LHCC) equations form the foundation of many applications in physics, engineering, and applied mathematics. These equations take the form:
		</p>

		<men xml:id="second-order-lhcc-de">
			a y'' + b y' + c y = 0
		</men>

		<p>
			where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are constants. In this section, we'll focus on understanding how the solutions depend on the roots of the characteristic equation, and how different types of roots lead to different forms of the general solution.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs>
		<title> Fundamental Solutions </title>

		<p>
			The first step in solving <xref ref="second-order-lhcc-de"/> is to get the characteristic equation using the methods in the previous section. Here, the characteristic equation is the <xref ref="solving-the-quadratic-equation" text="custom">quadratic equation</xref>
		</p>

		<men xml:id="second-order-lhcc-characteristic-equation">
			a r^2 + b r + c = 0
		</men>

		<p>
			Solving this quadratic equation using the <xref ref="quadratic-formula" text="custom">quadratic formula</xref> yields:
		</p>

		<men xml:id="second-order-lhcc-char-eqn-solns">
			r_1 = \frac{-b - \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}, \quad r_2 = \frac{-b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}
		</men>

		<p>
			Each root corresponds to a solution of the form <m>e^{r_1 x}</m> or <m>e^{r_2 x}</m>, called the <term>fundamental solutions</term> of the differential equation.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs>
		<title> The General Solution </title>
		
		<p>
			Once we know the fundamental solutions, the <term>superposition principle</term> tells us that any linear combination of them is also a solution. That is,
		</p>

		<me>
			y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}
		</me>

		<p>
			is a solution for any constants <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m>, as long as the two exponentials are not like-terms.
		</p>

		<p>
			There's one subtlety: if the two roots <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are equal, then the exponential solutions are like-terms and combine as a single term with only one arbitrary constant.<fn>This property is actually known as linear independence and also takes the domain (interval) of <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> into consideration.</fn> In that case, we modify one of the solutions by multiplying it by <m>x</m>, giving:
		</p>

		<me>
			y = c_1 e^{r x} + c_2 x e^{r x}.
		</me>

	    <p>
			This ensures the two solution parts form a complete solution.
		</p>

		<p>
			More importantly, it also leads to two possible cases for the general solution: 
			<dl width="wide">
				<li><title> Case 1 </title>
					<p>
						If <m>e^{r_1 x}</m> and <m>e^{r_2 x}</m> are not like-terms,<fn>This property is actually known as linear independence and also takes the domain (interval) of <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> into consideration.</fn> then the <em>general solution</em> is
						<me>c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}</me>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li><title> Case 2 </title>
					<p>
						If <m>e^{r_1 x}</m> and <m>e^{r_2 x}</m> are like-terms, then the general solution is
						<me>c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 x e^{r_2 x}</me>.
					</p>
					<p>
						Note that <m>e^{r_1 x}</m> and <m>e^{r_2 x}</m> are like-terms only if <m>r_1 = r_2</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</dl>
		</p>

		<p>
			In practice, it is standard to split Case 1 into two cases based on whether <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are real or complex numbers. This allows us to define each case based on the discriminant <m>(\Delta = b^2 - 4ac)</m> of the characteristic equation as follows: 
			<dl width="wide">
				<li><title> Case 1 <m>(\Delta &gt; 0)</m> </title>
					<p>
						<m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are real &amp; non-repeating.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li><title> Case 2 <m>(\Delta &lt; 0)</m> </title>
					<p>
						<m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are complex conjugates.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li><title> Case 3 <m>(\Delta = 0)</m> </title>
					<p>
						<m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are real &amp; repeating.
					</p>
				</li>
			</dl>
		</p>

		<p>
			Now, let's explore each of these cases in detail.
		</p>

		    <p>
      Altogether, there are three distinct cases based on the discriminant <m>\Delta = b^2 - 4ac</m> of the characteristic equation:
    </p>

	   <dl width="wide">
      <li><title> Case 1 <m>(\Delta &gt; 0)</m> </title>
        <p>
          Two distinct real roots: <m>r_1 \ne r_2</m>. The general solution is <m>y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li><title> Case 2 <m>(\Delta &lt; 0)</m> </title>
        <p>
          Complex conjugate roots: <m>r_1 = \alpha + i\beta</m>, <m>r_2 = \alpha - i\beta</m>. The solution is best written using sine and cosine:
        </p>
        <me>
          y = e^{\alpha x} (c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x)).
        </me>
      </li>
      <li><title> Case 3 <m>(\Delta = 0)</m> </title>
        <p>
          Repeated real root: <m>r_1 = r_2 = r</m>. The general solution is
        </p>
        <me>
          y = c_1 e^{r x} + c_2 x e^{r x}.
        </me>
      </li>
    </dl>

	    <p>
      In the next sections, we’ll explore examples of each case and see how the general solution adapts to the form of the characteristic roots.
    </p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> Case 1 <m>(\Delta &gt; 0)</m>: Real, Non-Repeating Solutions </title>

		<p>
			If <m>\Delta</m> is positive, then characteristic equation has the two non-equal real solutions:
		</p>

		<me>
			r_1 = \frac{-b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \quad \text{and} \quad
			r_2 = \frac{-b - \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}
		</me>,

		<p>
			so the general solution is
		</p>

		<me>
			y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}
		</me>.
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> Case 2 <m>(\Delta &lt; 0)</m>: Two Complex Solutions </title>
		<p>
			If <m>\Delta</m> is negative, the characteristic equation has two <em>complex conjugate solutions</em>:
		</p>

		<me>
			r_1 = \alpha + i \beta, \quad r_2 = \alpha - i \beta
		</me>

		<p>
			and the general solution is
		</p>

		<me>
			y = c_1 e^{(\alpha + i \beta)x} + c_2 e^{(\alpha - i \beta)x}
		</me>.

		<p>
			However, it is common to express this in terms of <em>sine</em> and <em>cosine</em> (via <xref ref="eulers-formula" text="title"/>):
		</p>

		<me>
			y = e^{\alpha x} (c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x))
		</me>.
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs><title> Case 3 <m>(\Delta = 0)</m>: Real, Repeating Solutions </title>
		<p>
			If <m>\Delta</m> is zero, then the characteristic equation has the <em>repeated solutions</em>
		</p>

		<me>
			r_1 = \frac{-b + 0}{2a} = \frac{-b}{2a}, \quad r_2 = \frac{-b - 0}{2a} = \frac{-b}{2a}
		</me>.

		<p>
			and the general solution, in this case, is
		</p>

		<me>
			y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 x e^{r_1 x}
		</me>

		<p>
			This modification ensures that our solution has two independent terms and preserves the desired properties of exponential functions that make them compatible solutions.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs>
		<title> Summary &amp; Examples </title>

		<p>
			The following summarizes the three different forms of the general solution to a second-order LHCC differential equation.
		</p>

		<assemblage><title> ✳️ 2nd-Order LHCC General Solution Cases </title>
			<p>
				Let <m>r_1</m>, <m>r_2</m> be the characteristic solutions of a second-order LHCC equation.
				<dl width="narrow">
					<li xml:id="lhcc-case-1">
						<title> Case 1 <m>(\Delta &gt; 0)</m> <m>\small \text{real &amp;}\ r_1 \ne r_2</m> </title>
						<p><me>y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}</me></p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="lhcc-case-2">
						<title> Case 2 <m>(\Delta &lt; 0)</m> <m>\small \text{complex &amp;}\ r=\alpha \pm i\beta</m> </title>
						<p><me>y = e^{\alpha x} (c_1 \cos(\beta x) + c_2 \sin(\beta x))</me></p>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="lhcc-case-3">
						<title> Case 3 <m>(\Delta = 0)</m> <m>\small \text{real &amp;}\ r_1 = r_2</m> </title>
						<p><me>y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 x e^{r_1 x}</me></p>
					</li>
				</dl>
			</p>
		</assemblage>

		<example><title> Case 1 Examples </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solutions to each 2nd-order LHCC equation.
				</p>

				<sidebyside widths="45% 55%">
					<p>
						<p>
							<m>\ds y'' - 5y' + 6y = 0</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							<solution>
								<p>
									The characteristic equation
								</p>

								<me>
									r^2 - 5r + 6 = 0
								</me>

								<p>
									can be factored as
								</p>

								<me>
									(r - 2)(r - 3) = 0
								</me>,

								<p>
									which gives the non-repeating real solutions
								</p>

								<me>
									r_1 = 2, \qquad r_2 = 3
								</me>
								
								<p>
									and the general solution
								</p>

								<me>
									y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{3x}
								</me>
							</solution>
						</p>
					</p>
					<p>
						<p>
							<m>\ds 5y'' + 13y' - 2y = 0</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							<solution>
								<p>
									The characteristic equation is 
								</p>

								<me>
									5r^2 + 9r - 2 = 0
								</me>.

								<p>
									Using the quadratic formula,
								</p>

								<md>
									<mrow> r	\amp = \frac{-9 \pm \sqrt{9^2 - 4 (5)(-2)}}{2 \cdot 5}	</mrow>
									<mrow>		\amp = \frac{-9 \pm \sqrt{121}}{10}						</mrow>
									<mrow>		\amp = \frac{-9 \pm 11}{10}								</mrow>
								</md>,

								<p>
									we get the real and non-repeating solutions
								</p>

								<me>
									r_1 = -2, \quad r_2 = \frac{1}{5}
								</me>,

								<p>
									which lead to the general solution
								</p>

								<me>
									y = c_1 e^{-2x} + c_2 e^{\frac{1}{5}x}
								</me>.
							</solution>
						</p>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
		</example>

		<example><title> Case 2 Examples </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solutions to each 2nd-order LHCC equation.
				</p>

				<sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
					<p>
						<p>
							<m>\ds \omega'' + 4\omega' + 5\omega = 0</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							<solution>
								<p>
									The characteristic equation
								</p>

								<me>
									r^2 + 4r + 5 = 0
								</me>.

								<p>
									is solved with the quadratic formula:
								</p>

								<md>
									<mrow> r	\amp = \frac{-4 \pm \sqrt{4^2 - 4 (1)(5)}}{2 \cdot 1}	</mrow>
									<mrow> 		\amp = \frac{-4 \pm 2i}{2} = -2 \pm i					</mrow>
								</md>.

								<p>
									Using <m>\alpha = -2</m> and <m>\beta = 1</m> in the complex formula, we get the general solution
								</p>

								<me>
									\omega(t) = c_1 e^{-2t}\left(c_1\cos t + c_2\sin t\right)
								</me>
							</solution>
						</p>
					</p>
					<p>
						<p>
							<m>\ds y'' + 25y = 0</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							<solution>
								<p>
									The characteristic equation
								</p>

								<me>
									r^2 + 25 = 0
								</me>

								<p>
									has the complex solutions
								</p>

								<me>
									r = \pm 5i
								</me>.

								<p>
									Using <m>\alpha = 0</m> and <m>\beta = 5</m> in the complex case formula, we get the general solution
								</p>

								<me>
									y = e^{0x}\left(c_1\cos(5x) + c_2\sin(5x)\right)
								</me>

								<p>
									or simply
								</p>

								<me>
									y = c_1\cos(5x) + c_2\sin(5x)
								</me>
							</solution>
						</p>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
		</example>

		<example><title> Case 3 Examples </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solutions to each 2nd-order LHCC equation.
				</p>

				<sidebyside widths="45% 55%">
					<p>
						<p>
							<m>\ds y'' + 4y' + 4y = 0</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							<solution>
								<p>
									The characteristic equation
								</p>

								<me>
									r^2 + 4r + 4 = 0
								</me>

								<p>
									can be factored as
								</p>

								<me>
									(r + 2)(r + 2) = 0
								</me>

								<p>
									which gives the repeating real solutions
								</p>

								<me>
									r_1 = -2, \qquad  r_2 = -2
								</me>

								<p>
									and modified general solution
								</p>

								<me>
									y = c_1 e^{-2x} + c_2 x e^{-2x}
								</me>.
							</solution>
						</p>
					</p>
					<p>
						<p>
							<m>\ds 16\frac{d^2q}{dr^2} - 8\frac{dq}{dr} + q = 0</m>
						</p>
						<p>
							<solution>
								<p>
									The characteristic equation is:
								</p>

								<me>
									16r^2 - 8r + 1 = 0
								</me>

								<p>
									Using the quadratic formula,
								</p>

								<md>
									<mrow> r	\amp = \frac{8 \pm \sqrt{8^2 - 4 (16)(1)}}{2 \cdot 16}	</mrow>
									<mrow>		\amp = \frac{8 \pm \sqrt{0}}{32}					</mrow>
									<mrow>		\amp = \frac{8}{32}	= \frac{1}{4}						</mrow>
								</md>,

								<p>
									This shows that <m> r = \frac{1}{4} </m> is a repeated root and the general solution is
								</p>

								<me>
									q(r) = c_1 e^{\frac{1}{4}r} + c_2 r e^{\frac{1}{4}r}
								</me>
								
							</solution>
						</p>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
		</example>

		<example><title> LHCC Equation General Solution </title>

			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the general solution to each of the equation below.
					</p>
					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="40% 60%">
							<p>
								<line>	1.	<m>\ds\ y'+\pi\ y = 0</m>	</line>
								<line>		<m></m>						</line>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										r + \pi = 0
									</me>,

									<p>
										has the solution <m>r = -\pi</m>. So, the equation has a fundamental solution of the form
									</p>

									<me>
										y_1 = e^{-\pi x}
									</me>.

									<p>
										Since the equation is first-order, this is the only fundamental solution.
									</p>

									<p>
										Therefore, the general solution is
									</p>

									<me>
										y = c_1 e^{-\pi x}
									</me>.
								</solution>
							</p>
						</sidebyside>

						<sidebyside widths="40% 60%">
							<p>
								<line>	2.	<m>\ds\ \omega'' - 7\omega' = 0</m>	</line>
								<line>		<m></m>						</line>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										r^2 - 7r = 0
									</me>,

									<p>
										has the solutions <m>r = 0,\ 7</m>. So, the fundamental solutions are
									</p>

									<me>
										\omega_1 = e^{0x} = 1, \quad \omega_2 = e^{7x}
									</me>.

									<p>
										Since these are not like-terms, they are independent and by the superposition principle, the general solution is
									</p>

									<me>
										\omega = c_1 + c_2\ e^{7x}
									</me>.
								</solution>
							</p>
						</sidebyside>
						<sidebyside widths="40% 60%">
							<p>
								<line>	3.	<m>\ds\ 2\frac{d^{3}M}{dt^{3}} - 6\frac{dM}{dt} = 0</m>	</line>
								<line>		<m></m>									</line>
							</p>
							<p>
								<solution>
									<p>
										The characteristic equation
									</p>

									<me>
										2r^3 - 6r = 0
									</me>,

									<p>
										can be factored as
									</p>

									<md>
										<mrow>	2r(r^2 - 3) = 0	\amp </mrow>
									</md>.

									<p>
										So, <m>r = 0,\ \sqrt{3},\ -\sqrt{3}\ </m>, giving the 3 independent fundamental solutions
									</p>

									<me>
										e^{0t}, \quad e^{\sqrt{3}t}, \quad e^{-\sqrt{3}t}
									</me>.

									<p>
										By the superposition principle, the general solution is
									</p>

									<me>
										M(t) = c_1 + c_2 e^{\sqrt{3}t} + c_3 e^{-\sqrt{3}t}
									</me>.
								</solution>
							</p>
						</sidebyside>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</p>
		</example>

		<p>
			These examples illustrate how second-order LHCC equations are solved using the <em>standard</em>, <em>repeating</em>, and <em>complex</em> cases discussed above. In the next section, we will see that a similar process can be generalized to higher-order LHCC equations.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<exercise><title>Answer the Following</title>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-1"><title> Discriminant of the Characteristic Equation </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If the discriminant of the characteristic equation is <m>-4</m>, then what kind of solutions does the characteristic equation have?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
			<choice correct="no">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Real and equal solutions
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>Incorrect. The discriminant is the number under the square root in the quadratic formula.</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice correct="no">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Real and unequal solutions
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>Incorrect. The discriminant is the number under the square root in the quadratic formula.</feedback>
			</choice>
			<choice correct="yes">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Complex solutions
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>Correct! A negative discriminant indicates the square root of a negative number in the quadratic formula, which results in the complex number <m>i</m>.</feedback>
			</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-2"><title> Classifying Characteristic Equations </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Match each characteristic equation to the correct root type.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					Good work! The discriminant helps classify root types.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r^2 - 4r + 3 = 0</m></premise>
					<response>Two distinct real roots</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r^2 - 6r + 9 = 0</m></premise>
					<response>One repeated real root</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r^2 + 4 = 0</m></premise>
					<response>Complex roots</response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-3"><title> Discriminant and Solution Type </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					For a second-order LHCC equation with characteristic equation,
				</p>

				<me>
					r^2 + br + c = 0
				</me>,

				<p>
					which expression determines the form of the general solution?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds b - 4c</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The discriminant is given by a squared term.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds b^2 - 4c</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The discriminant determines whether the characteristic roots are real and distinct, real and repeated, or complex.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds b^2 + 4c</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The correct expression involves a subtraction.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds \sqrt{b^2 - 4c}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The discriminant does not include a square root.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-4"><title> Solving the characteristic equation </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If the characteristic equation for an LHCC equation is <m>r^2 - 4r + 4 = 0</m>, what is the general solution?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 x e^{2x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>Correct! The solution <m>r = 2</m> has a multiplicity of 2.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{2x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. The solution <m>r = 2</m> has a multiplicity of 2.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{-2x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. Ensure you solve the charactistic equation correctly.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = e^{2x}(c_1 \cos(2x) + c_2 \sin(2x))</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. The characteristic equation does not have complex solutions.</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-5"><title> Purely Imaginary Characteristic Solutions </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
				<p>
					If a characteristic equation has roots <m>\pm i</m>, the general solution is
					<me>
						y = c_1 \cos x + c_2 \sin x
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					Correct! The complex exponentials transform into sine and cosine terms.
				</p>
			</feedback>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-second-order-lhcc-6"><title> Match the Characteristic &amp; General Solutions </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Match the characteristic solutions to the corresponding general solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r = 5 </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small C e^{5x} </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = 2, \ r_2 = 3 </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small C_1 e^{2x} + C_2 e^{3x} </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = -1, \ r_2 = -4 </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small C_1 e^{-x} + C_2 e^{-4x} </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = 3 + 2i, \ r_2 = 3 - 2i </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small e^{3x} (C_1 \cos(2x) + C_2 \sin(2x)) </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = -2, \ r_2 = -2 </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small (C_1 + C_2 x) e^{-2x} </m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\small r_1 = -1 + i, \ r_2 = -1 - i </m></premise>
					<response><m>\small e^{-x} (C_1 \cos(x) + C_2 \sin(x)) </m></response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</task>

	</exercise>

	<exercise><title> Answer the Following </title>

		<task label="chkpt-general-solution-1"><title> Structure of the General Solution </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the general solution of a second-order LHCC equation if the characteristic equation has distinct real solutions <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_1 e^{r_2 x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The constants must be distinct for each term.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = c_1 e^{r_1 x} + c_2 e^{r_2 x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! Each fundamental solution is multiplied by an arbitrary constant.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad y = e^{r_1 x} + e^{r_2 x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The general solution includes arbitrary constants.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-general-solution-2"><title> Understanding Arbitrary Constants </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					How many arbitrary integration constants appear in the general solution of an <m>n</m>-th order LHCC equation?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad 0</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The answer is higher.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad 1</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The answer is higher.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad 2</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The answer is higher.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad n-1</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The answer is higher.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad n</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! An <m>n</m>-th order LHCC equation must have <m>n</m> independent solutions, each multiplied by an arbitrary constant.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-general-solution-3"><title> Matching Equations to Solutions </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Match each characteristic equation to its corresponding general solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					Great work! The general solution is based on the characteristic solutions.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r^2 - 4 = 0</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{-2x}</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<response><m>y = c_1 e^{4x} + c_2 e^{-4x}</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r^2 - 3r - 4 = 0</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = c_1 e^{-x} + c_2 e^{4x}</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r^2 - 2 = 0</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = c_1 e^{\sqrt{2}x} + c_2 e^{-\sqrt{2}x}</m></response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-general-solution-4"><title> Building Solutions </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
				<p>
					If <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> are solutions to a second-order LHCC equation, then
					<me>
						y = 5y_1 - 2y_2
					</me>
					is also a solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					Correct! By the superposition principle, this combination is also a solution.
				</p>
			</feedback>
		</task>

		<task label="chkpt-general-solution-5"><title> Select the general solution </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the general solution for the first-order LHCC equation
					<me>y' - 2y = 0</me>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad y = ce^{2x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Check the sign of the exponent.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad y = ce^{-2x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The solution has the form <m>y = ce^{rx}</m>, where <m>r</m> is found from the characteristic equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad y = ce^{\frac12 x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Make sure to solve the characteristic equation correctly.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad y = ce^{-\frac12 x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. Check the coefficient of <m>y</m> in the original equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

	</exercise>

